The nice thing about a day out, when journaled about and photographed, is that you get to relive it more than once. 🤍  I get messages every week from people dealing with chronic illness, whether physical, mental, or both, who have read my articles.  There’s many of us in this world whose lives don’t look like other people’s.  We don’t often go out for a day of fun, we don’t travel, we barely leave home.  Most days I’m patient with it.  Lately it’s been hurting more.  Journaling is one of the greatest tools in my mental health tool belt.  Not only is it a safe space to get out emotion, but it is a place I can relive my healthy days again.  Jot down moments of joy.  Small joys maybe, but for some people very small things mean very big things.  Here’s to noticing and appreciating. 🤍

Merry Christmas and Happy Holidays to everyone, no matter what you are celebrating, from the little Dodge family.  We wish you peace, we wish you joy, we’re sending love.  On a personal note, this holiday for me is one where I celebrate my relationship with God and the gift He gave us.  Any strength I have, any joy in the midst of pain, any way I have of getting through the pain this world so constantly throws at me, is because I don’t feel alone in this fight.  I don’t feel like I’m leaning only on my own strength, but I feel like I have Love in my corner.  I think a lot of people misrepresent who God really is.  What I know Him to be is someone who loves all, no exceptions.  And that is what I wish for all of you.  Love, light, and peace.  I don’t open up a lot about my faith on here because I want it to be a place where anyone of any faith feels comfortable and safe.  But sometimes, like on Christmas, I just like to share that the joy I have is not my own.  It came down on Christmas day. ❤️

Happy New Year! 🥂🤍✨ Wishing you all a 2023 filled with peace, love given and love received, joy, and good things ahead.  2022 was by far the worst year of my life.  I’ve shared a little bit of it on here, some of it I’ve kept private.  My word for 2023 is “peace”. I want to hold it with both hands.  Figure it out.  Have it when times are good and when times are bad.  And I wish peace for all of you. 🤍

I find peace on Long Island, I just do.  It’s home, and no matter where we live, it always will be.  I love the cold weather, the ocean, bays, beaches, the snow on the sand, the fresh seafood, New York City close by.  So here’s a rare selfie, because I got to start this new year in my favorite place in this world.  For a short time anxiety and pain were interrupted by the ocean, the salt air, great food, and New York accents haha.  I’m thankful to start the new year here.  I hope 2023’s a good one.  One thing I know, if it is or isn’t, ✨I’m not going to give up✨…trying to find the good, spreading love as much as possible, and seeking peace.  Love you guys mucho mucho.  Happy New Year you strong, sweet humans. 🥂🤍✨

✨I’ve gone back and forth and back and forth if I’ve wanted to share this or not.  One minute I feel like, so many of you have reached out and told me that my honesty about chronic illness has helped you feel less alone and encouraged you.  I get DM’s and emails every week.  And that’s what I want my life to mean.  Helping people.  Spreading love, encouragement, making people feel less alone, making the invisible feel seen, bringing light to issues that should be a part of our conversations.  Like if I could accomplish that, I’d feel ok with my life.  On the other hand, there is something about being vulnerable that is terrifying.  Draining.  You worry if you’re oversharing.  You feel exhausted after sharing.  You feel exposed.  But I guess when it comes down to it, I want to live a life of authenticity.  And I want my life to serve a greater cause.  So here’s a look at the aesthetic of my craft space.  Which is honestly how it looks.  Pretty things make me feel better mentally and emotionally.  I truly enjoy hygge, decor, aesthetics.  But the last picture is what this past week has looked like.  I have been using photos I took all in one day to post.  I haven’t left bed.  I’ve barely been able to move.  One day it was even hard to eat and drink.  My reality is a stark juxtaposition of the lovely things I want to fill my life with, my ambitions and goals, and the really vicious attack my body has been under with chronic illness.  Both exist.  And I wanted to be authentic about both.  Even if it meant posting a less than flattering picture of me in bed haha.  If both exist for you, I hope you know you’re not alone.  If both exist for you, I hope you don’t give up, but also allow yourself grace and gentleness.  Sometimes pushing is fighting.  Sometimes resting is fighting. 🤍✨

✨If you’re a post reader, there is a bit of a personal story behind this post…

There are a number of things that effect my mental health, aside from anxiety, which I’ve dealt with forever.  Chronic Fatigue Syndrome and Fibromyalgia, two things I was diagnosed with at Duke, carry with them a funny thing… brain fog.  I legitimately have many moments throughout my day where I lose track of what I’m thinking, saying, can’t remember a word, deal with confusion, etc.  Not to mention how overwhelming fatigue and pain can be on cognitive function to begin with.  And let’s not even add that I need to do brain exercises to prevent early dementia post hysterectomy. 

I do word puzzles, but I want to be more proactive with it.  And more proactive with practicing peace, which is my word for 2023.  So I’m beginning two very specific journals this year.  This one is my meditation journal.  I’m personally using scripture, because I find the most peace meditating on scripture.  But you could use whatever- inspiring quotes, guided meditation, etc.  God just happens to be my hope in a very sad place.  But you can do you. 🤍

The second thing I’ll be doing is starting a reading journal.  I recently came across a post of someone who dealt with chronic illness who cried because she was finally able to finish a book after 6 years.  This is a real thing.  I love to read, but my energy and attention span have become a problem.  I think starting a reading bullet journal will help motivate me to read a little each day, and to complete books I’ve started, because I’ll have a bujo set aside for this purpose only.  I ordered one from @notebook_therapy , and I really can’t wait until it arrives. 

If you’ve made it this far, thank you.  I’d love to know if anyone can relate to this, or any positive, non judgemental thoughts. 🤍✨

It is the strangest thing, aging.  To feel the same on the inside, and look in the mirror to be met with someone new.  Someone you don’t really recognize.  She has slowly been becoming.  On the inside you feel young, vibrant.  Yes, age has changed you.  You’ve gained wisdom.  The crinkles around your eyes are patience, empathy, compassion.  The wispy hair is filled with insight, understanding, maturity.  But the spirit is a fluttery, youthful butterfly, knocking around in a slowly aging body.  There’s a disconnect there.  And it feels strange.  Youth discounts people after a certain age.  But you’re just starting to get to the good parts on the inside.  The parts where experience has molded you into someone who understands things deeper.  Who can see possibilities with not just hope but with patience.  Who can listen not just with compassion but with empathy.  IG says we need to show our faces once in a while, so I thought I would post a photo from yesterday.  But showing up in front of the camera has become harder.  I don’t think it should be.  So I’m talking about it.  I like to talk about real things haha.  And yeah, I airbrushed the sweaty, streaky makeup after a day out in the Carolina fields.  Don’t judge me, I’m taking things slow. 😂

Reading journal spread, “Fourth Wing”….

This is one of my favorite spreads in my reading journal, because I created my own artwork.  I was having trouble finding FW printables, so I made them myself haha.  But it was fun. 😉

What I loved about this book…. Violet being a chronically ill character, who knew things would be harder for her to accomplish than other people, but still fought and succeeded… was everything to me.  I can’t tell you how much this aspect of the story meant to me.  I thought the story/plot was amazing.  The dragons were… so good!!! 🥺 And even though I figured out most of the ending beforehand, I absolutely loved how it ended and set up for the next book.  This book kept me highly engaged, and I flew through it.

What I didn’t like…. Books, like art, are subjective.  We each have our own tastes.  I didn’t fully love the writing style.  I found the dialogue a little cheesy, and Violet a little immature.  And I don’t mind cursing, but the amount of it got to me a little.  I just felt like, if you want me to know a character is “tough”, write them that way.  Cursing every sentence just felt like a lazy way to communicate that. 🤷🏻‍♀️ Just my personal opinion haha.  But overall, amazing book.  And I can not wait until November to read book 2. 🐉✨ #fourthwing

“True love is the best thing in the world, except for cough drops.” ✨

“The Princess Bride: The Good Parts Version”, by William Goldman

I am so happy that I finally got around to reading this book. “The Princess Bride” is by far one of my favorite movies.  I was excited to see that most of my favorite quotes came directly from the book.  The book and the movie were so similar it surprised me. 

This book was hysterical, and at the same time it held a lot of truth and depth.  The ending made me into a blubbering mess.  S. Morgenstern, the original author, had one ending.  Goldman’s father, a romantic at heart, and the movie, had a different ending.  Goldman found somewhere in between.  And the reality of it just made me… cry.  And read it again and cry again haha.  I don’t know, at this stage in my life I feel like I appreciate realness. 🤷🏻‍♀️ 

Overall, I loved this book.  It went down to a 4⭐️ instead of 5⭐️ because I do feel like Buttercup is a bit objectified in this, and there’s an undercurrent of sexism.  I also feel like it’s a really old book, and it’s kind of a product of it’s time.  But that’s where it lost points for me.  But overall, great. “Do I love you?  My God, if your love were a grain of sand, mine would be a universe of beaches.” ✨

Do I make reading journal spreads on books I don’t like?  Yes, I do.  And I make them as pretty as possible, too, haha.  The reason why is that every book I finish feels like an accomplishment.  Whether I liked it or not.  It’s a win over chronic illness brain fog.  A victory.  And I feel proud of myself for finishing it.  It’s also sometimes a way to vent frustration.  I need a space sometimes to let it out haha. “Tea & Treachery” was just not for me.  In every way imaginable haha.  It took a 4 page spread to release my frustration. 😂 I’m sharing 2.5 of it.  Some books click, some don’t.  This was not my cup of… tea… but that’s ok. 🫖😉

Reading journal spread, “Anne of the Island”, L.M Montgomery 🍁

✨Some spoilers in spread; minor spoilers in caption…. 

I had the most complicated relationship with this book.  There were so many parts of it that were pure magic to me.  5⭐️ sections.  And then there were parts that were a big letdown, even made me upset.  It was hard to rate thing one.  5⭐️ parts, and 2.5⭐️ parts.  The rating here is not math haha.

What I loved… This book recaptured the magic the first book had, much more than book 2, (in my opinion). The quotes, the descriptions of nature, (and human nature), the wisdom, learning, growth, imagination, excitement… it was all back so beautifully in this book.  It is deep, mindful, lovely.  And contains a death scene so poignantly written I balled my eyes out, read it again, and full out cried again.  Also, the little cottage Anne and her friends rent and live in during their college years is the epitome of cozy and hygge.  That house will forever stay in my heart.

What I didn’t love… This book was written in 1915, and I understand that things were very different then.  But I felt like it was… too chaste at times.  There was a group of girls living together, in a respectable home, yet there had to be an elderly woman living with them, chaperoning them.  It kind of grieved me, because college is your time in life to spread your wings and fly, learn about yourself, be independent.  That felt a little squashed here, and it made me sad.  Also, major life events like weddings and pregnancies were glossed over, barely talked about.  And huge sections of time were just… not written about.  I think as a child I would have loved this book.  But as an adult reading it… it left so much to be desired.

This one was a personal glass case of emotions for me haha.  Any thoughts?  I know a lot of you are die hard Anne fans.  This one, for me, was incredibly beautiful and deep… and wanting.  It was both.  It was so weird that it was both!! 🫠🍁

I normally only share these grids in my stories, but I felt so happy and accomplished with filling up one of @perceivegrace ’s grids that I had to share haha.

I do feel like I need to explain some of the “success” behind this though.  November I experienced a huge fibromyalgia flare, with extreme fatigue and daily pain.  October was such a wonderful, functional month.  November was the opposite.  I also tend to deal with a lot of anxiety around the holidays.  Anxiety was horrible for me during most of this month.  And I used reading as a way to calm my mind, distract my thoughts, and also as a way to distract from the pain of fibro.  It is amazing what reading can do as a coping skill.  I will always be grateful for that. 🤍

That said, reading is also a way for me to “exercise” my brain, and try to combat the very real brain fog that accompanies fibromyalgia.  Each day I chose to read was a day I determined to fight my symptoms, not just distract from them.  It was a choice I made for my mental health and well being.  It’s a muscle I had to rebuild after fibro- concentration, retention, etc.  Like doing PT after an accident.  Rebuilding, retraining.  So this completed grid means a lot to me, it really does.  It means determination paid off.  It means I can accomplish things I wasn’t able to before.  And it also means that I have a very real coping skill through pain that gives me an escape, a healthy and beautiful escape.  That’s why I’m celebrating this completed grid. 🤍 If you’ve gotten this far in reading, thank you. 🤍🤍 What does reading do for you?

Let’s get the holiday/winter book journal reviews started! 🤍 I’m starting with Lovelight Farms, by B.K. Borison.

I really liked this book a lot.  I don’t think I loved it as much as most people do.  But I liked it quite a lot, and since reading it, it has stayed in my heart, and I think about it often.  What I loved… the setting of a Christmas tree farm was so magical and dreamy to me.  I loved Stella’s found family on her farm and in her friendship with Luka.  That will never not be one of my favorite tropes.  Luka was a book boyfriend dream haha.  I loved him. (Italian American from New York who’s been your best friend forever and turns into more… that story sounds vaguely familiar to me. 😂😉) 

What I didn’t love… I felt like I was supposed to love the supporting characters, and I really didn’t attach to them.  And the “misunderstanding” plot just got a little unbelievable and out of hand at the end.  I kind of wanted to shake Stella haha.  All around, a fun read and a cute holiday story.  Have you read it?  What did you think?

Next stop on the holiday/winter book reviews in my reading journal is Famous for a Living, by Melissa Ferguson. ❄️✨

Even though Christmas is in this one, I would say it was more of a winter read than a holiday one.  This is another book that has stayed with me, and I find myself thinking about often.

I wound up liking this book more than I thought I would.  It’s pretty cheesy, the romance aspect is a little bland, but there were some things I really loved.  I loved the two main characters, Cat and Zaiah.  The setting of the Montana mountains and a small town in winter was incredible. ❄️ And this book was surprisingly a lot about self growth, and the effect social media has on our lives, relationships, and mental health.  It made me like it more than I was expecting to. 🤍🌲

The next stop on the holiday/winter reading journal entries is All’s Fair in Love and Christmas, by Sarah Monzon. 🌲✨

So unfortunately I didn’t really like this book.  I always feel weird sharing a “negative” review, but the point of this journal is to encourage reading, and I count every book read as a good thing, not a bad thing.  Some you’ll connect with, and some you won’t. 🤷🏻‍♀️ 

What I liked… the two main characters, Mackenzie and Jeremy, were both admirable characters.  Always thinking of others, taking care of others, kind, generous, responsible.  I loved that there was social anxiety rep in this book, in the character of Mackenzie.  And I liked some real life elements, like illness and loss, sprinkled into what was honestly an over the top cheese fest haha.  I also liked the addition of faith in this book, although I didn’t really like how it was done a lot of the time.  It was awkwardly handled like so much of this unfortunately.

What I didn’t like… a bit too much to go into haha, but I’ll keep it brief.  There’s “cheese” that you’d expect reading a Christmas rom-com.  And then there’s over-the-top cheesiness that makes you cringe.  That’s what this one felt like to me.  A big job promotion based on, not ability, but who has the most Christmas spirit?  I mean, does Hallmark even go that far? 😂 The ending was downright painful for me, between Mackenzie acting really inappropriately and being praised for it, and their boss making an admission that made me want to throw my iPad across the room. 🤦🏻‍♀️ I wanted to like this one, I really did.  But the whole thing was just so awkward and cringey.

That said, I am happy I read it, I did enjoy parts of this story, and any read book is a good thing to me.  Even if it wasn’t my cup of tea. ☕️ If you’ve read this and enjoyed it, that honestly makes me happy.  Sometimes I just need to get out frustration in my reviews haha. 🤷🏻‍♀️

One of my favorite things to do this time of year is to walk around cities and towns and see their trees and holiday decorations.  I just love it so much.  This year I made it a little special, and bought three books to remember our little day trips.  I’d like to share them. 🤍

Book one…. When we were in Greenville, SC, we stopped by the Grand Bohemian Lodge @grandbohemianlodgegreenville , and were surprised by a little German-style Christmas market.  One of the booths, @themidnightpostshop , had the most gorgeous illustrations turned into greeting cards, bookmarks, stickers, prints, and… a woodland creature mystery book!! (I’m such a fan of the Shady Hollow series, I was thrilled to find this!) The copies were gorgeous hardcovers, (the first picture shows the book under the dust jacket), with beautiful illustrations, and they were signed by the author.  I picked up a matching bookmark and sticker, and I can’t wait to dive into this.  Definitely a special memento from a very special, festive day. 🌲🤍 (Some more photos in stories.)✨

Book 2/City 2…. “Bright Lights, Big Christmas”, by Mary Kay Andrews/Spartanburg, SC ✨

Even though this book was very middle of the road for me, (I gave it a 2.75/5 ⭐️), this night I was so… happy.  Purely happy. 

I don’t get nights out a lot.  In fact, I can’t even remember the last time I felt healthy enough to be out at night.  @blueridge_snail had suggested a local bookshop, @hubcitybookshop , and I was so happy not just to be able to go, but to have a night out wandering around downtown Spartanburg, seeing the lights and Christmas decorations, the outdoor fires, the small shops.  My heart was filled with such pure joy that night.  And even though I didn’t love love the book, having a memento of that experience was really special to me.  Especially a beautiful signed copy. 🤍✨

Last book/last city… I saved the best for last. 😉 “Twilight Falls”, by @juneau_black /Brevard, NC. 🌲✨

“Shady Hollow” is the book that got me back into reading.  I picked up a copy at @highland_books in Brevard, (my favorite local city since moving to the Carolinas). This book reignited my love of reading, and resulted in me, simply put, becoming a reader again.

I love this series of anthropomorphic animals, living in the coziest woodland town, solving murders.  It is simply the best.  Warm coffees, tight knit community, spunky fox 🦊 reporter.  What more could you ask for haha.  When the fourth novel came out, I headed back to @highland_books to purchase it, since it is where I purchased the first one. (I’m a bit sentimental. 🙃)

As for Brevard, it has become my place of peace, escape, and joy, these past 6 years.  I’ve felt out of place since moving, like a puzzle piece that hasn’t fit.  This small city fits my heart, and never fails to cheer me up. 🤍

Finally, thank you @juneau_black for a series as cozy as warm cup of coffee from Joe’s Mug. ☕️

I’m going to give a ✨meh✨ review to a book everyone seems to love.  I have only seen good reviews on this one.  People seem to love it.  For me, it just didn’t land.

One reason is just personal preference.  I tend to like classic mysteries, not thrillers.  This one bordered a little more on thriller.  But aside from that I found this… very formulaic, predictable, even cliche. 🤷🏻‍♀️ Slight spoilers, nothing major… there is a “twist” at part two of this book that I suspected since the very beginning.  Although it was fun, I wouldn’t say it was shocking.  And the very end of this just made me roll my eyes.  It didn’t make sense with the rest of the book, and just seemed so cliche to me.  I don’t know, this just didn’t impress me that much. 🤷🏻‍♀️

That said, I did feel like it was well written, with a great pace.  I read it in one sitting, and it definitely draws you in.  And the setting, and English country estate, is my favorite setting to read.  Equally beautiful and spooky haha. Overall though, this just wasn’t my personal cup of tea. ☕️ Have you read it?  What did you think?

I feel like it’s been a while since I last did an intro post, and there have been a lot of new faces, especially new bookstagram friends, since my last one.  So here’s a little intro… 😊

I’m Kim, and Dodges and Daisies is named after my little fam, consisting of my husband and rescue pups, and my favorite flower.  Jake and I met when I was 10 years old, and he broke my toe while sparring in a karate class. 😂 We were best friends in high school, and started dating midway into college.  He’s still my best bud all these years later.

I have a degree in psychology and worked in that field for a little while.  I was also a photographer for 11 years.  Severe chronic illness made me unable to work, so I started Dodges and Daisies as a way to try to bring in some income on days I was healthy enough to be active.  It wound up being a place where I found true friendships, wonderful people, a supportive community, and was able to turn life long hobbies into opportunities.  I’ve been journaling, snailmailing, and reading since childhood, and now I’m able to chat about all three on here. 😉

I have a true love for my home state of New York.  All of it- Long Island, where I’m from, New York City, where my parents are from, and upstate New York, which I find beautiful.  I talk openly about chronic illness, women’s health advocacy, and mental health advocacy, because I think being honest and authentic is a way to make people feel less alone, and also better problems associated with issues.  Chronic illness has really impacted my life, and although I don’t like to focus on it, I do like to be honest about it. 

The last few years as I’ve gotten older I’ve also thought a lot about how important it is to focus on the positives of aging, and letting women know that their worth is not in being young and shiny, but in their depth of heart, soul, and mind.  We get better with age in so many ways, and I would love to be a small contributor to the overall conversation of making maturing less scary.
